igne, Ath, Henegouwen, België"},"en":{"environ 1100–11 mai 1144":"about 1100–11 May 1144","1100–1144":"1100–1144","1109–Female":"1109–Deceased","1112–1183":"1112–1183","1105–1176":"1105–1176","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1140–1172":"1140–1172","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1085–Male":"1085–Deceased","–1144":"–1144","1190":"1190","about 1140":"about 1140","environ 1100":"about 1100","1176":"1176","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1172":"1172","1183":"1183","11 mai 1144":"11 May 1144","1105":"1105","1112":"1112","1144":"1144","1100":"1100","1109":"1109","France":"France","Ligne, Ath, Hainaut, Belgique":"Ligne, Ath, Hainaut, Belgium","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Fontaines","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Normand, Pierre, Emile, Fernand, Lucien, Marcel, Adelard, Henri, Jacques, Laurent.","French and Walloon: topographic name for someone living near a spring or well, from Old French <i>fontaine</i>, from Late Latin <i>fontana</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>fons</i> (see   Font  ); or a habitational name from Fontaine, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Fountaine  .","Shortened form of French   Lafontaine  , a variant of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Fontenot","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Ulysse, Andrus, Alcide, Andre, Edouard, Lucien, Marise, Monique, Remy.","French: variant of <b>Fonteneau</b> (and, in North America, an altered form of this), a topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from any of several places mainly in the westcentral part of France so named. The surname <i>Fontenot</i> is very rare in France.","History: Jean-Louis Fonteneau/Fontenot from Montierneuf in Vienne, France, married Louise-Angélique Henry in Mobile, AL, in 1726."]},{"name":"Fontenelle","meanings":["French: topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from (La) Fontenelle, the name of several places in various parts of France, of the same origin."]},{"name":"Fontenette","meanings":["French: topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from Fontenette, the name of several places mainly in the central part of France, of the same origin."]},{"name":"Fountain","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from one or more of the places in France named Fontaine, Fonteyne, or Lafontaine (see   Fontaine  ).","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a spring or well, from Middle English <i>fontayne</i> (Old French <i>fontaine</i>) ‘spring, fountain’, sometimes with a plural <i>-s</i>, and synonymous with   Well  , of which <i>Fountain(es)</i> may sometimes have been a translation."]},{"name":"Font","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Juan, Luis, Miguel, Rafael, Eduardo, Raul, Eugenio, Pedro, Roberto, Aida.","Catalan and southern French: topographic name for someone living near a spring or well, Catalan and Occitan <i>font</i> ‘spring, well’ (from Latin <i>fons</i>, genitive <i>fontis</i>).","English: variant of   Fant  ."]},{"name":"Fontan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Angel, Benigno, Carlos, Jose, Juana, Manuel, Pedro, Adolfo, Aida, Alfredo, Candido, Emilia.","Spanish and Galician (<b>Fontán</b>): habitational name from any of the many places called Fontán, from <i>fontán</i> ‘spring’.","French: variant of   Fontaine  ."]}]},{"name":"Marguerite","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Margaret  , also used in the English-speaking world, where its use has been reinforced by the fact that the name was adopted in the 19th century for a garden flower, a large cultivated variety of daisy. <i>Margaret</i> was earlier used in English as a dialect word denoting the ox-eye daisy, and the French equivalent was borrowed into English just in time to catch the vogue for deriving girls' names from vocabulary words denoting flowers.  See also  Daisy ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Marguerite de Fontaines was born about 1100 as the daughter of Wauthier II de Fontaine-l'Evêque and Marie de Zottegem. She had at least 5 sons and 1 daughter with Seigneur Thierry I de Ligne. She died on 11 May 1144, in Ligne, Ath, Hainaut, Belgium, at the age of 45."},"et":{"environ 1100–11 mai 1144":"umbes 1100–11. mai 1144","1100–1144":"1100–1144","1109–Female":"1109–Surnud","1112–1183":"1112–1183","1105–1176":"1105–1176","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1140–1172":"1140–1172","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1085–Male":"1085–Surnud","–1144":"–1144","1190":"1190","about 1140":"umbes 1140","environ 1100":"umbes 1100","1176":"1176","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1172":"1172","1183":"1183","11 mai 1144":"11. mai 1144","1105":"1105","1112":"1112","1144":"1144","1100":"1100","1109":"1109","France":"Prantsusmaa","Ligne, Ath, Hainaut, Belgique":"Ligne, Ath, Hainaut, Belgia"},"fi":{"environ 1100–11 mai 1144":"noin 1100–11. toukokuuta 1144","1100–1144":"1100–1144","1109–Female":"1109–Kuollu